On February [XXX], 2025 at 3:39 AM MT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in Chandler, Arizona was in a collision involving an SUV on [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was traveling northbound on [XXX] in the left lane towards the intersection of [XXX]. The SUV crossed into the intersection with W. Flint Street from the dedicated right turn lane and continued traveling straight onto the far-side sidewalk. The SUV then departed the roadway, striking a fire hydrant and a utility bollard before making contact with a street light. A Zoox vehicle (Vehicle 1) in autonomous mode was in the right lane, traveling east on [XXX] in Las Vegas. An SUV (Vehicle 2) to the left of the Zoox vehicle, was traveling ahead in the same direction in the adjacent lane. Just as the Zoox vehicle entered the intersection, the SUV suddenly veered right across the path of the Zoox vehicle. The Zoox vehicle braked hard in response to the encroaching SUV, the Zoox vehicle operator then disengaged from autonomy, and shortly after, the front passenger side of the SUV made contact with the front driver side of the Zoox vehicle. The SUV rotated counterclockwise after impact and the rear passenger side of the SUV made contact with the rear driver side of the Zoox vehicle. The SUV sustained major damage with airbag deployment and the Zoox vehicle sustained moderate damage to the driver side. Both vehicles were towed from the scene. The police and EMS arrived at the scene. The Zoox vehicle operator reported "body soreness" and "limping" a few hours after the collision.

On January [XXX], 2025 at 6:07 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in San Francisco, CA was in a collision involving a passenger vehicle near the intersection of [XXX] and [XXX].

While the Waymo AV and the other passenger vehicle were stopped, an SUV approached from behind at an extreme rate of speed and made contact with the passenger vehicle behind the Waymo AV, which then made contact with the rear bumper of the Waymo AV. According to the San Francisco Police Department, the Waymo AV then began to rotate clockwise and, as it was rotating, the front of the SUV made contact with the passenger side of the Waymo AV. The rear of the Waymo AV then made contact with the rear driver side corner of another passenger car that had just begun to proceed straight on northbound [XXX]. According to the San Francisco Police Department, at least two other vehicles were involved in the crash and one of the occupants of the vehicles involved in the crash and a domestic animal were declared deceased at the scene. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AVs Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV, the passenger vehicle behind the Waymo AV, and the SUV sustained severe damage. The extent of the damage to the other three vehicles is currently unknown. Waymo received notice that five passengers in four of the vehicles involved sustained injuries of varying severity. 
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because of a fatality. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On December [XXX], 2024 at 8:28 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in Los Angeles, CA was in a collision involving two SUV's, a passenger car, and a pick up truck on [XXX] at [XXX].

As the oncoming SUV entered the intersection, it made contact with a passenger car traveling east on [XXX].  The oncoming SUV continued through the intersection and swerved to narrowly miss a pedestrian before making contact with the front of the Waymo AV and the front driver side of a stationary pickup truck to the right of the Waymo AV.  The impact from the oncoming SUV caused the Waymo AV to contact another SUV that was also stationary to the left of the Wayo AV at the red traffic light.  The Waymo AV test driver transitioned to manual mode immediately before the oncoming SUV made contact.  At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was not engaged and a test driver was operating the Waymo AV in manual mode.  The Waymo AV sustained damage to the front and rear of the vehicle, necessitating a tow from the scene.  The oncoming SUV sustained damage to the front and driver side.  The stationary SUV that was contacted sustained damage to the passenger side.  The Waymo test driver was transported to a local hospital for medical treatment.
Transdev Alternative Services is reporting this crash under Request no. 1 of Standing General order 2021-01 because an individual involved was transported from the scene to a hospital for medical treatment, a vehicle involved was towed away, and because of airbag deployment.  Transdev may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.  This is a duplicate of NHTSA Report ID: 30270-9476-2.

Cruise submits this updated report to confirm there was no physical contact between the AV and the cyclist and to provide additional details about this incident. As the cyclist approached quickly from behind the AV, they moved from the right side of the road to the left side and attempted to maneuver around the AV, between the AV and a parked vehicle. On December 15, 2023, GM Cruise Holdings LLC ("Cruise") filed an update Incident Report (the "Report") under the Second Amended Standing General Order 2021-01, dated April 5, 2023 (the "Order") General Motors LLC (GM) manufactured the Cruise-operated motor vehicle involved in the incident summarized in the Incident Report. Because GM is also a Reporting Entity under the Order, GM is submitting a duplicate of the redacted public copy of the Report. GM has selected "Unknown" in the "ADS version" and "ODD time" fields solely to avoid a second submission of nonpublic Cruise CBI GM is in possession of Cruise's responses to these fields, and incorporates Cruise's responses into this submission by reference. GM's submission is based on facts supplied to GM by Cruise. GM has not investigated the alleged incident and currently believes, based on a reasonable inquiry, that it has no independent knowledge of the facts in the Report. (Reference file: 30412-6395-4).

Cruise is submitting this updated report to indicate in the Post-Crash Information section that it has received a California Highway Patrol Traffic Collision Report in connection with the reported incident.  There are no other changes to Cruise's previous submission (30412-6395-3): A Cruise autonomous vehicle (AV), operating in driverless autonomous mode, was at a complete stop in response to a red light on southbound [XXX] at the intersection with [XXX]. A dark colored Nissan Sentra was also stopped in the adjacent lane to the left of the AV. As the Nissan Sentra and the AV proceeded through the intersection after the light turned green, a pedestrian entered the crosswalk on the opposite side of [XXX] across from the vehicles and proceeded through the intersection against a red light. The pedestrian passed completely through the AVs lane of travel but stopped mid-crosswalk in front of the Nissan Sentra. Shortly thereafter, the Nissan Sentra made contact with the pedestrian, deflecting the pedestrian in front of the AV. The AV braked aggressively but, shortly thereafter, made contact with the pedestrian. The AV then attempted to pull over out of traffic, pulling the individual forward, rather than remaining stationary. The driver of the Nissan Sentra left the scene shortly after the collision. Police and Emergency Medical Services (EMS) were called to the scene and the pedestrian was transported by EMS. On November 2, 2023, Cruise submitted a voluntary recall report to NHTSA relating to the AVs response after the collision, based on updated analysis that Cruise performed since the filing of the previous submissions.

On November [XXX], 2023 at 10:43 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a passenger car on [XXX] at [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was traveling northbound in the left lane on [XXX] and stopped at a red light at the intersection with [XXX] alongside a passenger vehicle in the right lane. After the light turned green, both the Waymo AV and the adjacent passenger car proceeded into the intersection. While in the intersection, a passenger car traveling west on [XXX] ran the red light and the front left corner and left side of this vehicle made contact with the front right of the Waymo AV and the front of the adjacent passenger car. After impact, the vehicle that ran the red light struck pedestrians that had been standing on the sidewalk on the northwest corner of the intersection. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AVs Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. All three vehicles sustained damage and were towed from the scene.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because an individual involved was transported from the scene to a hospital for medical treatment, and a vehicle involved was towed away. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

Narrative: A Zoox vehicle in autonomy was stopped at a stop sign on southbound [XXX] at [XXX] waiting for a crossing vehicle to clear the intersection, when it was rear-ended by an e-scooter rider. The e-scooter rider initially passed the slowing Zoox vehicle while traveling on northbound [XXX], but then made a mid-block U-turn and rode into the rear of the then-stopped Zoox vehicle in a visibly deliberate manner. The contact resulted in minor scratches on the rear bumper of the Zoox vehicle. The e-scooter rider did not initially indicate that they were injured, and the Zoox operator drove through the intersection to a safe pullover location to assess the damage however, the e-scooter rider later indicated that their "foot hurts". The Police and EMS were then called to the scene, and the e-scooter rider apparently received medical attention and was released. This update provides complete information to date for this incident.

Cruise is submitting this updated report to correct the pre-crash speed and provide additional information in the narrative since the previous submission (30412-6395-2) on October 12, 2023. A Cruise autonomous vehicle (AV), operating in driverless autonomous mode, was at a complete stop in response to a red light on southbound [XXX] at the intersection with [XXX]. A dark colored Nissan Sentra was also stopped in the adjacent lane to the left of the AV. As the Nissan Sentra and the AV proceeded through the intersection after the light turned green, a pedestrian entered the crosswalk on the opposite side of [XXX] across from the vehicles and proceeded through the intersection against a red light. The pedestrian passed completely through the AVs lane of travel but stopped mid-crosswalk in front of the Nissan Sentra. Shortly thereafter, the Nissan Sentra made contact with the pedestrian, deflecting the pedestrian in front of the AV. The AV braked aggressively but, shortly thereafter, made contact with the pedestrian. The AV then attempted to pull over out of traffic, pulling the individual forward, rather than remaining stationary. The driver of the Nissan Sentra left the scene shortly after the collision. Police and Emergency Medical Services (EMS) were called to the scene and the pedestrian was transported by EMS. On November 2, 2023, Cruise submitted a voluntary recall report to NHTSA relating to the AVs response after the collision, based on updated analysis that Cruise performed since the filing of the previous submissions. [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION]

As the pickup truck pulled out of the parking spot, it initiated a multi-turn maneuver and reversed into the parked Waymo AV. Federal Regulatory Exemption?: Part 591 Exemption granted by permission letter from NHTSA
Narrative:
On June 23, 2023, Motional informed HMNA's NASO of a crash incident occurring on June [XXX], 2023, at 9:42 PM PDT, involving a Hyundai IONIQ 5 test vehicle operating in proprietary ADS autonomous mode with a safety driver at the wheel and a safety operator in the front passenger seat.  According to Motional, the test vehicle was travelling northbound in the left-most of two left turn lanes on a local road at approximately 10 mph.  The test vehicle then braked for an approaching taxi in the adjacent lane that appeared to be crossing into the Motional test vehicle's lane and was rear-ended by a silver Toyota from behind.  The Toyota vehicle fled the scene of the accident.
Hyundai understands that the equipment and software used during the test is proprietary to Motional and not used as OEM equipment in any Hyundai/Genesis vehicle produced for sale to the general public.  Hyundai currently does not offer an ADS feature on any vehicle offered for sale in the U.S. market.

On June [XXX], 2023 at 11:18 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in Los Angeles, California was in a collision involving a pick-up truck on [XXX] at [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was traveling eastbound on [XXX] and stopped at a stop sign at the intersection of [XXX] when a pick-up truck approached the Waymo AV from behind and made contact with the rear of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AVs Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode, and a test driver was present (in the drivers seating position).
The Waymo AV test driver then took manual control of the Waymo AV and the pick-up truck then made contact with the rear of the Waymo AV again. The Waymo AV test driver pulled towards the side of the road and stopped. TThe pick-up truck then made contact with the rear of the Waymo AV again and when the test driver of the Waymo AV resumed movement, the pick-up truck followed the Waymo AV and repeatedly made further contact with the Waymo AV. At one point the pick-up truck driver verbally harassed the Waymo AV test driver. The Waymo AV test driver was eventually able to elude the pickup truck and wait nearby for law enforcement to arrive. The Waymo AV sustained damage.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vehicle involved was towed away. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

The test driver (in the driver's seating position) transitioned to manual mode and continued to slow the Waymo AV. The motorcyclist attempted to turn behind the Waymo AV and made contact with the left rear corner of the Waymo AV. The motorcyclist remained upright and rode away without stopping to provide any information. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was not engaged and a test driver was operating the Waymo AV in manual mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage to the driver's side of the rear bumper.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vulnerable road user (motorcyclist) was involved. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available. This report was submitted from the Pacific time zone on the required date.

On November [XXX], 2021 at 8:02 PM PST a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ('Waymo AV') operating in San Francisco, CA was in a collision involving a passenger vehicle at [XXX], [XXX], and [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was traveling southbound on [XXX], a narrow road with vehicles parked on both sides, and approaching the intersection with [XXX] and [XXX]. A passenger vehicle approaching from the right of the Waymo AV on eastbound [XXX] made a left turn in front of the Waymo AV to head northbound on [XXX]. The Waymo AV slowed to a near stop and nudged to its right in order to share the narrow road with the oncoming vehicle and then came to a stop at the stop sign as the oncoming vehicle completed its turn. At approximately 5 mph, the turning passenger vehicle made contact with Waymo AV's sensor hardware housing on the driver side rear corner fender of the stopped Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode, and a test driver was present (in the driver's seating position). The Waymo AV sustained minor damage to the sensor hardware housing (which was the reason for towing the Waymo AV) and the passenger vehicle left the scene without exchanging information.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vehicle involved was towed away. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.
